        <div xml:id="AN20-kilavi"></div>
        <div xml:id="AN20">
            <lg type="edition"><l>perunī raḻuvat tentai tanta</l>
<l>koḻumī ṉuṇaṅkaṟ paṭupuḷ ḷōppi</l>
<l>yekkarp puṉṉai yiṉṉiḻa lacaiic</l>
<l>cekkar ñeṇṭiṉ kuṇṭaḷai keṇṭi</l>
<l>ñāḻa <choice><seg>loṭuṅkuci<supplied>ṉai</supplied>t</seg><seg>lōṅkuciṉait</seg></choice> toṭutta koṭuṅkaḻit</l>
<l>tāḻai vīḻkayiṟ ṟūca ṟūṅkik</l>
<l>koṇṭa liṭumaṇaṟ kuravai muṉaiyiṉ</l>
<l>veṇṭalaip puṇari yāyamō ṭāṭi</l>
<l>maṇippūm paintaḻai taii <choice><seg>yaṇittakaip</seg><seg>yaṇittakap</seg></choice></l>
<l>palpūṅ kāṉa lalkiṉam varutal</l>
<l><choice><seg>kavvai</seg><seg>kauvai</seg></choice> nallaṇaṅ kuṟṟa vivvūrk</l>
<l>koṭitaṟi <choice><seg>peṇṭirc</seg><seg>peṇṭir</seg></choice> coṟkoṇ ṭaṉṉai</l>
<l>kaṭikoṇ ṭaṉa<supplied>ḷē</supplied> tōḻi peruntuṟai</l>
<l>yellaiyu miravu meṉṉātu kalleṉa</l>
<l><choice><seg>vallava</seg><seg>valava</seg></choice> ṉāynta vaṇpari</l>
<l>nilavumaṇaṟ koṭkumōr tēruṇ <supplied>ṭe</supplied>ṉavē.</l></lg>
            <lg type="translation" xml:lang="en">
<l>Taking in the words of the cruelly knowing women</l>
<l>of this village, in the grip of the good<note place="foot">kavvai nal aṇaṅk’ uṟṟa: here the attribute nal is used in order to disambigue aṇaṅku as a personal, not an abstract malignant force and thus to mark the phrase as a metaphor; the old commentary glosses with: alar āki[ya] pēyar piṭittal.</note> demon of gossip,</l>
<l>about [his] coming to us who abided<note place="foot">alkiṉam probably cannot be taken as a finite verb here, unless we want to read it as an unmarked sentence end. It has a genitive relation to what follows; in other words, it is not a case of the traditional muṟṟeccam (which ought to be glossable by alkiṉam āy). Still, the “regular” perfective participial noun of a verb of the 5th class should be alkiyam.</note> in the seashore grove with many flowers</l>
<l rend="indent">	fit for decoration,</l>
<l rend="indent">	knitting together sapphire flowers [and] fresh foliage,</l>
<l rend="indent">	playing with [our] companions in the white-headed waves</l>
<l rend="indent">	when having enough of the Kuravai dance in the sand put down by the east wind,</l>
<l rend="indent">	hanging in the swing on ropes from the aerial roots of the screwpine<note place="foot">This line can be interpreted in a different way, depending on whether we understand vīḻ as an “aerial root” or as a verbal root meaning “to descend”. Then the translation could be: “hanging in the swing on ropes descending from the Tāḻai tree | by the winding backwaters that is linked linked to the high branches of the Ñāḻal tree”. In this case the tokutta would be slightly awkward, and since TVG ascertains that a Tāḻai tree is too feeble to carry a swing, the former solution might be preferable.</note></l>
<l rend="indent">	by the winding backwaters, linked to the subservient branches of the Ñāḻal tree,</l>
<l rend="indent">	digging up the deep holes of the red crabs,</l>
<l rend="indent">	resting in the pleasing shade of the mastwood trees in the dunes,</l>
<l rend="indent">	chasing away the birds coming down on the drying [spread] of fat fish</l>
<l rend="indent">	brought by father from the depth of the great water,</l>
<l rend="indent">	mother</l>
<l>has set up a watch, friend,</l>
<l>saying “there is one chariot that rolls through the moonlit sand</l>
<l>in generous motion<note place="foot">Here it is equally well possible to read vaṇ pari as a metonymy (or a bahuvrīhi) for horse: “those with generous motion”. Then we would have a “chariot ... with generously moving [horses] selected by the skilful man“ (or the “charioteer”, according to the reading of strand 2).</note> chosen by the skillful man,</l>
<l>noisily, without telling day from night, at the big ghat.”</l></lg>
        </div>
    </body>
